). The subtribe 
Opsiina
is the largest of the 4 subtribes, with 28 genera and more than 250 species (Du 
et al.
, 2019; 

).

The genus
Satsumanus
was established by Ishihara in 1953 based on the type species
Eutettix satsumae Matsumura 1914
. The genus is characterized by its aedeagus with a pair of ventral processes, forewings reticulated without rhomboidal marble spots at the middle (
,
;
). The genus is closely related to
Opsius Fieber, 1866
and
Opsianus Linnavuori, 1960
(
). Nevertheless,
Satsumanus
can be distinguished from the later genera by the placement of the ocelli, the crown slightly longer medially than next to eyes, the male pygofer with dorso-posterior margin produced into a lobe and macrosetae restricted to the caudal area, and the gonopores large and far from the shaft apices (
). At present, there are 6 species known from Oriental (2 spp.) and Australian (4 spp.) regions (
;
,
;
;
;
). In this paper, a new species,
Satsumanus robusta
sp. nov. ,
is described and illustrated from India .

